properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong frontal system will reach the northern Yukon tonight. Snow and winds of 70 km/h are forecast to develop this evening. The snow and wind will combine to produce blizzard conditions tonight. The blizzard will end by early Wednesday morning when winds ease. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.
Expires: 2019-11-20T15:43:08-00:00

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard today and tonight. A low pressure system is bringing snow and blowing snow to areas along the Hudson Bay coast. Winds will strengthen to north 50 or 60 km/h this morning along with stronger gusts and dropping temperatures. This combination will allow visibilities to drop to the blizzard criterion of 400 metres. Blizzard conditions will start easing at Arviat this evening and at Rankin Inlet Thursday morning as the snow pulls out and winds start to diminish. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
Expires: 2019-11-21T01:23:24-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall on Thursday and Thursday night. Total snowfall: 15 to 25 cm. Locations: Newfoundland's interior. Time span: Thursday morning to Friday afternoon. Remarks: A developing storm is forecast to bring significant snowfall to the island. The heaviest snowfall will occur somewhere over Newfoundland's interior, with more of a mixture of snow and rain closer to the coast. Along Newfoundland's east coast, precipitation will fall mostly as rain. The location and total of the maximum snowfall amounts remains uncertain at this time. Temperatures are expected to be mild, which may lead to significantly reduced accumulation. Variations in the track of the system could also shift where the most snow is expected to fall. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Smog Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: High concentrations of fine particulate matter are expected and will result in poor air quality this morning. ### Smog especially affects asthmatic children and people with respiratory ailments or heart disease. It is therefore recommended that these individuals avoid intense physical activity outdoors until the smog warning is lifted. In Quebec, wood heating is the main source of fine particles that contribute to smog during winter. This activity generates the largest number of these particulates, more than industrial activities and transportation. Additional information: To learn more about the Info-Smog program, go to Environment Canada’s website at www.canada.ca/info-smog-program. For air quality indexes in Quebec, visit the website of the Ministère de l'Environnement et de la Lutte contre les changements climatiques at www.iqa.environnement.gouv.qc.ca/contenu/index_en.asp. For the air quality index in Montréal, visit the Réseau de surveillance de la qualité de l’air de la Ville de Montréal’s website at www.rsqa.qc.ca (french only). To learn more about the effects of smog on your health in Québec, visit the Ministère de la Santé et des Services sociaux’s website at www.quebec.ca/en/health. You can also visit the Direction régionale de santé publique du CIUSSS du Centre-Sud-de-l’Île-de-Montréal at www.santemontreal.qc.ca/en/public. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A low pressure system tracking across the northern United States spread snow into southwestern Saskatchewan this afternoon. The snow is pushing into southeastern regions late this evening. Snow at times heavy will continue overnight and then taper off to light in the morning as the system moves into the Dakotas. Total accumulations of 10 to 15 cm are likely over much of the Shaunavon and Assiniboia regions with slightly lesser amounts toward Estevan and Carlyle. Snowfall amounts will diminish quickly to the north of the Trans-Canada Highway. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
